\f0\fs28 \cf0 Composition mode blocks everything else out so that it\'92s just you and your words. To enter composition mode, try one of the following:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\li720\fi-720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}Click on the square, grey icon next to the blue inspector icon in the toolbar.\
{\listtext	\'95	}Hit 
\f1\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::0>
\f2\b Opt-Cmd-F
\f1\b0 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::0>
\f0\fs28  on the keyboard.\
{\listtext	\'95	}Go to 
\f1\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::0>
\f2\b View > Enter Composition Mode
\f1\b0 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::0>
\f0\fs28 .\
\pard\tx720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 You will now be looking at nothing but your text. (When first entering composition mode, you\'92ll see a message about typewriter scrolling\'97if you would like to learn more about that feature, see the \'93Typewriter Scrolling\'94 bookmark in the inspector.)\
Here\'92s what you need to know about composition mode:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\li720\fi-720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}When you move the mouse to the bottom of the screen, a control bar appears. This allows you to change the text zoom, the position and width of the virtual paper, and fade the background in and out. It also has buttons to bring up the keywords panel and inspector.\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\li1440\fi-1440\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl1\cf0 {\listtext	
\f3 \uc0\u8259 
\f0 	}
\f1\fs24 \cf3 <$Scr_Cs::1>
\f2\i\b Tip:
\f1\i0\b0 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::1>
\f0\fs28  Holding down the Option key while the control bar is visible changes the \'93Paper Width\'94 slider to \'93Paper Height\'94.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\tx1120\li720\fi-720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}You can customise the look of composition mode in the \'93Appearance\'94 pane of the Preferences. By default, the regular text colour is overridden to appear as white on a dark grey-blue background, but you can change this to use black-on-white, green-on-black or anything you want.\
{\listtext	\'95	}You can set a background image for composition mode via 
\f1\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::0>
\f2\b Project > Project Settings\'85
\f1\b0 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::0>
\f0\fs28 \
{\listtext	\'95	}Switch documents in composition mode by going to 
\f1\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::0>
\f2\b Navigate > Go To
\f1\b0 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::0>
\f0\fs28  in the main menu, or by using the \'93Go To\'94 button in the control bar. (Also, the keyboard shortcuts 
\f1\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::0>
\f2\b Opt-Cmd-Up
\f1\b0 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::0>
\f0\fs28  and 
\f1\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::0>
\f2\b Opt-Cmd-Down
\f1\b0 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::0>
\f0\fs28  navigate to the previous and next document in the binder, and 
\f1\fs24 \cf4 <$Scr_Cs::0>
\f2\b Cmd-[
\f1\b0 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::0>
\f0\fs28  and 
\f1\fs24 \cf4 <$Scr_Cs::0>
\f2\b Cmd-]
\f1\b0 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::0>
\f0\fs28  navigate back and forth through the document history.)\
{\listtext	\'95	}Hit 
\f1\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::0>
\f2\b Opt-Cmd-F
\f1\b0 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::0>
\f0\fs28  or Escape to leave composition mode (or use the button on the right in the control bar).\
